description:
Files: runtime/src/heap.rs

When gc_minor() promotes a young survivor but old_top >= old_end (old block full mid-promotion), escalate to gc_major() rather than overflowing. The old block must never overflow silently.

Detection: in gc_minor(), before each cheney_forward into old space, check if old_top + object_size > old_end. If so, abort minor GC, restore state, and call gc_major() instead.

Alternative (simpler for v1): pre-flight check at the start of gc_minor(). If young bytes_used() > old free space (old_end - old_top), skip minor and call gc_major() directly. This is conservative but safe and avoids mid-GC state restoration.

Implement the pre-flight check (simpler):
  if young_top - young_start > old_end - old_top {
      gc_major(roots, mailbox);
      return;
  }

Tests: when old block has insufficient space for all young live objects, gc_major() is called instead of gc_minor(). gc_minor() completes successfully when old has sufficient space.
